---
import BeforeAfter from './BeforeAfter.astro';
import heroOld from '../assets/spottr/hero-old.jpg';
import heroNew from '../assets/spottr/hero-new.jpg';
import onboardingOld from '../assets/spottr/onboarding-old.jpg';
import onboardingNew from '../assets/spottr/onboarding-new.jpg';
---
{/* Spottr's "room": the shipped app's amber accent is scoped locally here,
    leaving the portfolio's terracotta as the house accent everywhere else. */}
<section
  id="spottr"
  class="bg-paper border-t border-paper-dark"
  style="--color-accent: #D9A53B; --color-accent-warm: #E8C06A; --color-accent-faint: #F6EBD0;"
>
  <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-6 py-24">

    <!-- Header -->
    <div data-reveal class="flex items-center gap-4 mb-16">
      <p class="font-body text-sm text-ink-muted uppercase tracking-widest">Case Study 01</p>
      <span class="flex-1 border-t border-paper-dark"></span>
      <span class="font-body text-xs text-accent uppercase tracking-wider">Product Thinking</span>
    </div>

    <h2 data-reveal class="font-display text-5xl md:text-6xl font-light text-ink mb-4" style="line-height: var(--leading-tight);">
      Spottr
    </h2>
    <p data-reveal data-reveal-delay="1" class="font-display text-2xl font-light text-ink-muted mb-12" style="font-style: italic;">
      A gym app that gets out of its own way.
    </p>

    <!-- Sticky running head — pins below the title and tracks the current beat -->
    <div class="spottr-marker" aria-hidden="true">
      <span class="spottr-marker__study">01 — Spottr</span>
      <span class="spottr-marker__beat" data-beat-label>The problem</span>
    </div>

    <!-- Problem -->
    <div data-beat="The problem" class="mb-20">
      <p data-reveal class="font-body text-xs text-ink-faint uppercase tracking-widest mb-6">The problem</p>

      <p data-reveal class="font-body text-lg text-ink mb-6" style="line-height: var(--leading-loose);">
        You just joined a gym. You want to get stronger but you don't really know what you're doing.
        There's someone across the floor who clearly does. You could ask — but you don't.
        They look busy. They might be annoyed. You don't want to be <em>that person</em>.
      </p>

      <p data-reveal class="font-body text-lg text-ink mb-6" style="line-height: var(--leading-loose);">
        They see you too. They'd actually enjoy helping. But they don't want to walk up
        uninvited and give advice nobody asked for. So nothing happens.
      </p>

      <div class="quote-wrap my-10">
        <span class="quote-wrap__mark" aria-hidden="true">&rdquo;</span>
        <blockquote
          data-reveal data-reveal-delay="1"
          class="border-l-2 border-accent pl-6"
          style="border-left-color: var(--color-accent);"
        >
          <p class="font-display text-2xl font-light text-ink" style="font-style: italic; line-height: var(--leading-snug);">
            "Both sides want to connect. Neither side moves. That's the gym intimidation deadlock."
          </p>
        </blockquote>
      </div>

      <p data-reveal class="font-body text-lg text-ink" style="line-height: var(--leading-loose);">
        Most "gym buddy" apps try to solve this with profiles and matching —
        a dating-app model transplanted to the gym floor. That's the wrong diagnosis.
        The problem isn't discovery. It's <strong>permission</strong>.
      </p>
    </div>

    <!-- Insight -->
    <div data-reveal data-beat="The insight" class="mb-20 bg-paper-mid border border-paper-dark rounded-lg p-8 md:p-12">
      <p class="font-body text-xs text-ink-faint uppercase tracking-widest mb-6">The insight</p>

      <p class="font-body text-lg text-ink mb-6" style="line-height: var(--leading-loose);">
        People need a signal that the other person is actually there, actually open,
        and actually expecting contact. Context does the permission work — not profiles.
      </p>

      <p class="font-body text-lg text-ink" style="line-height: var(--leading-loose);">
        Spottr's solution: <strong>geolocation-gated live presence</strong> + <strong>chat-first contact</strong>.
        You only appear as "live" when you're physically checked in at the gym.
        Contact happens through the app — no approaching in person unless both people agree.
        The shared location and shared moment eliminate the awkwardness before it starts.
      </p>
    </div>

    <!-- Design override moment -->
    <div data-beat="The decision" class="mb-20">
      <p data-reveal class="font-body text-xs text-ink-faint uppercase tracking-widest mb-6">The decision that mattered most</p>

      <p data-reveal class="font-body text-lg text-ink mb-6" style="line-height: var(--leading-loose);">
        The first design that came back was black-and-white, high-contrast, premium-feeling.
        Clean lines. Dark mode. The kind of thing that looks impressive in a Dribbble screenshot.
      </p>

      <p data-reveal data-reveal-delay="1" class="font-display text-3xl font-light text-ink my-8" style="line-height: var(--leading-snug);">
        I rejected it.
      </p>

      <p data-reveal class="font-body text-lg text-ink mb-6" style="line-height: var(--leading-loose);">
        Not because it was bad design. Because it was <em>wrong</em> design.
        The product's entire reason to exist is reducing gym intimidation —
        and the design was intimidating. The aesthetic contradicted the soul of the app.
      </p>

      <p data-reveal class="font-body text-lg text-ink mb-10" style="line-height: var(--leading-loose);">
        I gave the AI a new brief: warm, friendly, approachable — the antithesis
        of the "serious gym" look. It generated a warm light palette. That's the version that shipped.
      </p>

      <!-- The proof: the rejected design wipes into the shipped one -->
      <BeforeAfter
        before={heroOld}
        after={heroNew}
        beforeAlt="Spottr's rejected first design — black, high-contrast, dark mode"
        afterAlt="Spottr's shipped design — warm, light, approachable"
        beforeLabel="What came back"
        afterLabel="What shipped"
      />

      <div data-reveal class="border border-accent-faint bg-accent-faint rounded-lg px-6 py-4 mt-10">
        <p class="font-body text-sm text-ink" style="line-height: var(--leading-normal);">
          <strong>The lesson isn't about taste.</strong>
          It's about knowing what the thing is <em>for</em> — and overriding the output when it misses that.
          That's not a technical skill. That's judgment.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Iteration: the status system I rebuilt around mood -->
    <div data-beat="The iteration" class="mb-20">
      <p data-reveal class="font-body text-xs text-ink-faint uppercase tracking-widest mb-6">The feature I rebuilt</p>

      <p data-reveal class="font-body text-lg text-ink mb-6" style="line-height: var(--leading-loose);">
        The first version had a status system. When you checked in, you chose one —
        Happy to Help, Need Guidance, or Just Training — so the room knew what kind of session
        you were having.
      </p>

      <p data-reveal class="font-body text-lg text-ink mb-6" style="line-height: var(--leading-loose);">
        It broke the moment I used it on myself. To set a status, you had to publicly declare
        your competence: announce you were the expert, or admit you were the one who needed help.
      </p>

      <p data-reveal data-reveal-delay="1" class="font-display text-3xl font-light text-ink my-8" style="line-height: var(--leading-snug);">
        I'd rebuilt the exact intimidation the app exists to remove.
      </p>

      <p data-reveal class="font-body text-lg text-ink mb-6" style="line-height: var(--leading-loose);">
        So I tore it out and rebuilt it around mood instead of role — Locked in, Finding my rhythm,
        Taking it easy, In between sets. None of them rank you. They just say where your head is.
      </p>

      <p data-reveal class="font-body text-lg text-ink mb-10" style="line-height: var(--leading-loose);">
        Then willingness to connect became its own, separate thing: a single "welcome a hello" toggle.
        You can be locked in and still open to a hello, or taking it easy and left alone. Those were
        never the same question — the first design had just fused them together.
      </p>

      <!-- The proof: the status system wipes into the mood + toggle rebuild -->
      <BeforeAfter
        before={onboardingOld}
        after={onboardingNew}
        beforeAlt="Spottr's rejected status system — Happy to Help, Need Guidance, Just Training"
        afterAlt="Spottr's shipped mood system — Locked in, Finding my rhythm, Taking it easy, plus a welcome-a-hello toggle"
        beforeLabel="Status system"
        afterLabel="Mood + a toggle"
      />

      <div data-reveal class="border border-accent-faint bg-accent-faint rounded-lg px-6 py-4 mt-10">
        <p class="font-body text-sm text-ink" style="line-height: var(--leading-normal);">
          <strong>Same lesson, twice.</strong>
          The mechanic was never the problem — it was what it forced people to say about themselves.
          A feature can work perfectly and still carry the wrong message. Catching that before a user
          feels it is the actual job.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Build -->
    <div data-reveal data-beat="How it was built" class="mb-20">
      <p class="font-body text-xs text-ink-faint uppercase tracking-widest mb-6">How it was built</p>

      <p class="font-body text-lg text-ink mb-6" style="line-height: var(--leading-loose);">
        Built in plan mode. Every feature started as a written brief — what it should do,
        what it shouldn't do, what decisions I was making and why.
        I read the Supabase and Expo documentation before implementing, not after things broke.
        Prompts were engineered like contractor briefs: specific, constrained, with explicit constraints.
      </p>

      <p class="font-body text-lg text-ink" style="line-height: var(--leading-loose);">
        The AI handled execution. I handled direction.
      </p>
    </div>

    <!-- Architecture -->
    <div data-reveal class="mb-20">
      <p class="font-body text-xs text-ink-faint uppercase tracking-widest mb-4">Architecture</p>
      <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-light text-ink mb-8" style="line-height: var(--leading-snug);">How it's assembled</h3>

      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-3 gap-4 mb-10">
        <div class="bg-paper-mid border border-paper-dark rounded-lg p-6">
          <p class="font-body text-xs text-accent uppercase tracking-wider mb-3">Mobile App</p>
          <p class="font-body text-sm text-ink-muted mb-3" style="line-height: var(--leading-normal);">React Native · Expo · expo-router</p>
          <p class="font-body text-sm text-ink-faint" style="line-height: var(--leading-normal);">Auth, onboarding, live member list, messaging, QR check-in, push notifications</p>
        </div>
        <div class="bg-paper-mid border border-paper-dark rounded-lg p-6">
          <p class="font-body text-xs text-accent uppercase tracking-wider mb-3">Admin Portal</p>
          <p class="font-body text-sm text-ink-muted mb-3" style="line-height: var(--leading-normal);">Next.js 14 · Vercel · SSR auth</p>
          <p class="font-body text-sm text-ink-faint" style="line-height: var(--leading-normal);">Platform HQ and gym-partner portals, server-side Supabase sessions</p>
        </div>
        <div class="bg-paper-mid border border-paper-dark rounded-lg p-6">
          <p class="font-body text-xs text-accent uppercase tracking-wider mb-3">Backend</p>
          <p class="font-body text-sm text-ink-muted mb-3" style="line-height: var(--leading-normal);">Postgres · RLS · Realtime · Edge Functions · pg_cron</p>
          <p class="font-body text-sm text-ink-faint" style="line-height: var(--leading-normal);">JWT auth, row-level security on all tables, WebSocket live updates, Deno serverless functions, scheduled cleanup jobs</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div data-reveal class="border-l-4 border-accent rounded-r-lg px-6 py-5" style="background-color: var(--color-accent-faint);">
        <p class="font-body text-xs text-accent uppercase tracking-widest mb-3">What makes it real</p>
        <p class="font-display text-lg font-light text-ink mb-4" style="line-height: var(--leading-snug);">The constraint is at the data layer.</p>
        <p class="font-body text-sm text-ink" style="line-height: var(--leading-normal);">
          Block relationships enforced by RLS — blocked users cannot see each other's check-ins,
          not because the app hides them, but because the database returns nothing.
          The one-intro limit is a UNIQUE constraint on thread pairs, not an application rule.
          Safety and integrity built in, not bolted on.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Stack + status -->
    <div data-reveal class="flex flex-col sm:flex-row sm:items-end justify-between gap-6 pt-8 border-t border-paper-dark">
      <div>
        <p class="font-body text-xs text-ink-faint uppercase tracking-widest mb-3">Stack</p>
        <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-2">
          {["React Native", "Expo", "Supabase"].map((tech) => (
            <span class="font-body text-xs text-ink-muted border border-paper-dark px-2 py-1 rounded">
              {tech}
            </span>
          ))}
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="text-right">
        <span class="font-body text-xs text-accent uppercase tracking-wider bg-accent-faint px-3 py-1 rounded-full">
          Beta · Launching soon
        </span>
      </div>
    </div>

  </div>
</section>
